00:00:25.742 --> 00:00:27.450
IAIN STEWART: All
right, so last time, we

00:00:27.450 --> 00:00:30.240
were talking about degrees
of freedom in SCET.

00:00:30.240 --> 00:00:33.720
And I drew these two pictures
and emphasized to you

00:00:33.720 --> 00:00:35.670
that the difference
between these two pictures

00:00:35.670 --> 00:00:38.970
is really where the degrees of
freedom live in momentum space.

00:00:38.970 --> 00:00:45.040
So this is the P
minus P plus plane.

00:00:45.040 --> 00:00:47.640
And unlike most
effective field theories,

00:00:47.640 --> 00:00:49.560
in this effective
field theory we

00:00:49.560 --> 00:00:51.000
have degrees of
freedom that have

00:00:51.000 --> 00:00:54.700
to be identified by two
variables rather than just one.

00:00:54.700 --> 00:00:58.560
So we need two variables
to say where collinears are

00:00:58.560 --> 00:01:01.560
or where softs are.

00:01:01.560 --> 00:01:03.600
And there was
generically, I said,

00:01:03.600 --> 00:01:05.550
a dependence on the process.

00:01:05.550 --> 00:01:09.510
So SCET, or what degrees
of freedom you need,

00:01:09.510 --> 00:01:12.120
depends what you're studying.

00:01:12.120 --> 00:01:14.220
And it's generically
not the case

00:01:14.220 --> 00:01:15.660
that these two
effective theories

00:01:15.660 --> 00:01:17.340
that I wrote down
for you will describe

00:01:17.340 --> 00:01:19.940
every possible process.

00:01:19.940 --> 00:01:21.690
In fact, SCET, of
course, won't describe

00:01:21.690 --> 00:01:22.750
every possible process.

00:01:22.750 --> 00:01:24.375
So what effective
field theory you need

00:01:24.375 --> 00:01:26.310
depends on what
you're looking at.

00:01:26.310 --> 00:01:30.360
It just turns out that these
two sets of degrees of freedom

00:01:30.360 --> 00:01:31.860
that I wrote down
to you do describe

00:01:31.860 --> 00:01:33.120
a lot of different processes.

00:01:33.120 --> 00:01:36.720
And that's why the language
of SCETI and SCETII is useful,

00:01:36.720 --> 00:01:38.040
but there's no guarantees.

00:01:38.040 --> 00:01:40.880
You could run into a
process that requires

00:01:40.880 --> 00:01:41.880
more degrees of freedom.

00:01:41.880 --> 00:01:44.160
And there are
examples of processes

00:01:44.160 --> 00:01:47.070
that require more degrees
of freedom than this,

00:01:47.070 --> 00:01:48.850
but this is still a
useful starting point.

00:01:48.850 --> 00:01:51.060
And this is where we'll start.

00:01:56.690 --> 00:01:58.850
And then we were talking
a little bit about fields

00:01:58.850 --> 00:01:59.750
last time.

00:01:59.750 --> 00:02:03.980
And one thing I derived for
you was that the collinear

00:02:03.980 --> 00:02:07.415
field has a power counting that
makes it scale like lambda.

00:02:11.620 --> 00:02:12.860
This is the collinear quark.

00:02:18.780 --> 00:02:21.330
And then at the end of lecture,
we also derived a formula

00:02:21.330 --> 00:02:23.370
for the collinear gluons.

00:02:23.370 --> 00:02:28.000
So if we write down components
of the collinear gluon plus,

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:30.720
minus, and perp--

00:02:30.720 --> 00:02:32.820
we remember what
these notation means.

00:02:32.820 --> 00:02:38.970
This means n dot A. And
this means n bar dot A.

00:02:38.970 --> 00:02:45.304
And we figured out that
the scaling for these guys

00:02:45.304 --> 00:02:47.180
is lambda squared 1 lambda.

00:02:47.180 --> 00:02:49.550
And we said that that was
nice because we could put them

00:02:49.550 --> 00:02:57.260
together with a derivative and
have a covariant derivative,

00:02:57.260 --> 00:02:59.205
which I wrote in
terms of momenta just

00:02:59.205 --> 00:03:00.080
to sort of emphasize.

00:03:07.610 --> 00:03:14.998
So, if you like, this
is momentum space,

00:03:14.998 --> 00:03:16.790
that these guys had
the same power counting

00:03:16.790 --> 00:03:19.093
in the different components.

00:03:19.093 --> 00:03:21.260
And so when we come and
talk about gauge invariance,

00:03:21.260 --> 00:03:22.820
this fact that they have
the same power counting

00:03:22.820 --> 00:03:25.237
in the different components
will, of course, be important.

00:03:25.237 --> 00:03:29.720
Because what gauge invariance
does is ties momenta to gluons.

00:03:29.720 --> 00:03:31.970
And if we didn't have
the same power counting

00:03:31.970 --> 00:03:33.980
in the different
components, then we

00:03:33.980 --> 00:03:36.860
would not have a gauge
field corresponding

00:03:36.860 --> 00:03:39.710
to a certain momenta.

00:03:39.710 --> 00:03:41.702
OK, so another way of
arguing that they should

00:03:41.702 --> 00:03:43.910
have the same power counting
would have been directly

00:03:43.910 --> 00:03:47.430
from gauge invariance.

00:03:47.430 --> 00:03:51.430
All right, I'd like
to continue there.

00:03:51.430 --> 00:03:53.190
The one thing that
you'll note, which

00:03:53.190 --> 00:03:56.100
is unusual from an effective
theory point of view,

00:03:56.100 --> 00:04:00.210
is there's a set of fields that
have no suppression at all.

00:04:00.210 --> 00:04:03.180
These A n minus gluon
fields just scale like one.

00:04:11.367 --> 00:04:13.200
So when you have
dimensional power counting,

00:04:13.200 --> 00:04:14.492
all the fields have dimensions.

00:04:14.492 --> 00:04:15.900
You add more fields.

00:04:15.900 --> 00:04:17.070
You get higher dimensions.

00:04:17.070 --> 00:04:18.720
You get suppression.

00:04:18.720 --> 00:04:20.760
Here, with this
lambda power counting,

00:04:20.760 --> 00:04:24.420
there's a component of the gauge
field that has no suppression.

00:04:24.420 --> 00:04:27.420
We can add as many
of them as we want.

00:04:27.420 --> 00:04:29.070
And that costs nothing.

00:04:42.910 --> 00:04:46.940
So let's do that and
see what happens.

00:04:58.940 --> 00:05:03.820
So a priori, you might think
that this is really bad

00:05:03.820 --> 00:05:06.400
because you could have
an infinite number

00:05:06.400 --> 00:05:08.050
of different operators
at lowest order

00:05:08.050 --> 00:05:11.770
just with a different number
of these A n minus fields.

00:05:11.770 --> 00:05:15.895
And we'll see that actually
things are not so bad,

00:05:15.895 --> 00:05:18.020
but I think it's best to
do that by way of example.

00:05:22.790 --> 00:05:26.080
So we'll consider an example
that just has one collinear

00:05:26.080 --> 00:05:31.360
particle in it for simplicity.

00:05:31.360 --> 00:05:33.940
And we can do that by
having a heavy particle that

00:05:33.940 --> 00:05:37.300
carries a lot of energy
decay to a light particle,

00:05:37.300 --> 00:05:40.360
like a B quark decaying
to an up quark.

00:05:40.360 --> 00:05:47.650
So in QCD, our current
would just be u bar gamma b.

00:05:47.650 --> 00:05:51.100
Gamma would be
left-handed current.

00:05:57.530 --> 00:05:59.855
And we can consider the
B quark to be in HQET.

00:06:11.060 --> 00:06:16.000
And we have an energetic u quark
as what we want to consider.

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:19.275
It's not the only
possibility, but we

00:06:19.275 --> 00:06:21.400
could pump all the momentum
out through the current

00:06:21.400 --> 00:06:23.700
into the leptons into the e nu.

00:06:23.700 --> 00:06:26.490
But let's pump energy
into the up quark,

00:06:26.490 --> 00:06:27.510
so that it's energetic.

00:06:31.260 --> 00:06:33.234
So here's the current in QCD.

00:06:36.100 --> 00:06:38.690
b goes to u.

00:06:38.690 --> 00:06:41.540
And the notation that
I'll use for this

00:06:41.540 --> 00:06:45.110
is a double line
for the heavy quark

00:06:45.110 --> 00:06:47.270
and then a dashed line
for the collinear quark.

00:06:50.260 --> 00:06:53.770
So this guy is going to be
described by an hv field.

00:06:53.770 --> 00:06:56.320
This guy is going to be
described by Cn field.

00:06:56.320 --> 00:06:58.420
This is production, so
this will be a Cn bar.

00:07:12.170 --> 00:07:14.680
So I'll reserve this
notation of dashed lines

00:07:14.680 --> 00:07:17.647
for collinear quark propagators.

00:07:20.330 --> 00:07:24.680
OK, so the simple
minded thing is just

00:07:24.680 --> 00:07:27.047
to write down an
effective theory current

00:07:27.047 --> 00:07:29.630
where I replace the full theory
fields by the effective theory

00:07:29.630 --> 00:07:30.130
fields.

00:07:30.130 --> 00:07:35.840
I replace the up quark, an up
quark that's a Cn collinear

00:07:35.840 --> 00:07:38.150
field in some direction.

00:07:38.150 --> 00:07:42.230
And I replace the heavy quark
by an hv for the b quark.

00:07:46.250 --> 00:07:49.130
Then, effectively, that would
be the tree level matching

00:07:49.130 --> 00:07:51.710
between this diagram
and that diagram

00:07:51.710 --> 00:07:54.395
or the tree level matching
from that particular diagram.

00:07:58.310 --> 00:08:01.490
But let's consider adding
these A n minus gluons,

00:08:01.490 --> 00:08:06.290
since they were things that
we could add to the current.

00:08:06.290 --> 00:08:08.270
So we can add any number
of A n minuses here,

00:08:08.270 --> 00:08:10.687
and we'd have something that's
the same order in the power

00:08:10.687 --> 00:08:12.080
counting.

00:08:12.080 --> 00:08:23.420
So let's consider another
diagram in QCD, where I just

00:08:23.420 --> 00:08:24.867
attach an A n minus gluon.

00:08:24.867 --> 00:08:26.450
And I'll attach it
to the heavy quark.

00:08:31.940 --> 00:08:34.490
So I have a different
number of external fields,

00:08:34.490 --> 00:08:36.860
but this one costs
me nothing when

00:08:36.860 --> 00:08:40.159
I go to the effective theory.

00:08:40.159 --> 00:08:43.789
Let's call this momentum here k.

00:08:43.789 --> 00:08:46.782
We'll call this guy here q.

00:08:46.782 --> 00:08:49.980
And this guy here
we'll just say is MbV.

00:08:54.040 --> 00:08:59.580
So then k is MbV plus q.

00:09:05.736 --> 00:09:07.560
And I can write q
out in components

00:09:07.560 --> 00:09:09.500
since it's a collinear particle.

00:09:09.500 --> 00:09:13.500
And if I want to
identify the big piece,

00:09:13.500 --> 00:09:16.380
then that would be
the n bar dot qp's.

00:09:16.380 --> 00:09:18.930
So remember last time, from
looking at coordinates,

00:09:18.930 --> 00:09:21.670
we can write out any vector
in terms of the coordinates.

00:09:21.670 --> 00:09:23.878
And it's useful to do that
since the coordinates have

00:09:23.878 --> 00:09:25.845
a different power counter.

00:09:25.845 --> 00:09:27.720
Now, what's going to
appear in the propagator

00:09:27.720 --> 00:09:33.280
here is k squared minus m
squared minus Mb squared.

00:09:33.280 --> 00:09:36.640
So let's look at k squared.

00:09:36.640 --> 00:09:39.960
So if I square this term,
I just get Mb squared.

00:09:39.960 --> 00:09:42.600
If I square this term, I
get 0, but then there's

00:09:42.600 --> 00:09:43.700
a cross term as well.

00:09:52.095 --> 00:09:53.220
And then there's some dots.

00:09:53.220 --> 00:09:55.680
And the dots are indicating
terms that are suppressed.

00:10:03.490 --> 00:10:09.700
And so if I look at k squared
minus M squared, then that's n

00:10:09.700 --> 00:10:13.744
dot v Mb n bar dot q.

00:10:13.744 --> 00:10:19.125
And this order lambda to the
0 since the momentum n bar

00:10:19.125 --> 00:10:22.300
dot q was order lambda to the 0.

00:10:22.300 --> 00:10:29.410
So there's no power
counting to the propagator.

00:10:29.410 --> 00:10:31.525
Another way of saying
it is this propagator

00:10:31.525 --> 00:10:34.540
is off-shell by a hard amount.

00:10:34.540 --> 00:10:35.880
These scales are hard.

00:10:35.880 --> 00:10:37.900
And if I go back
to my picture, that

00:10:37.900 --> 00:10:44.050
means they're up here
in this purple region,

00:10:44.050 --> 00:10:46.450
purple box around this.

00:10:46.450 --> 00:10:50.920
OK, so the degree of freedom,
which is this purple propagator

00:10:50.920 --> 00:10:55.100
is actually living up
in that purple region.

00:10:55.100 --> 00:11:02.280
It's something we have
to integrate out, OK?

00:11:02.280 --> 00:11:03.090
So let's do that.

00:11:08.520 --> 00:11:11.262
So integrating it out just
means expanding the diagram.

00:11:11.262 --> 00:11:12.970
And I've already
expanded the propagator,

00:11:12.970 --> 00:11:15.760
so there's the denominators.

00:11:15.760 --> 00:11:17.957
We just have to
expand the numerator.

00:11:31.140 --> 00:11:31.640
OK.

00:11:34.230 --> 00:11:39.000
Let me write out A n mu,
but we replace the spinner

00:11:39.000 --> 00:11:39.840
by the field.

00:11:42.420 --> 00:11:45.480
And I'll start by just writing
in the full propagator,

00:11:45.480 --> 00:11:48.000
and then we'll
start expanding it.

00:11:55.780 --> 00:12:02.170
I'm using a convention here for
the gluon interaction in QCD,

00:12:02.170 --> 00:12:04.990
which is plus igTA gamma mu.

00:12:09.720 --> 00:12:13.927
So there's the full theory.

00:12:13.927 --> 00:12:15.510
All I've done is
take the full theory.

00:12:15.510 --> 00:12:18.472
And rather than write spinners
and a polarization vector,

00:12:18.472 --> 00:12:19.680
I've just written the fields.

00:12:19.680 --> 00:12:21.210
Because I'm, in
the end, interested

00:12:21.210 --> 00:12:24.300
in looking at what
kind of operator I get.

00:12:24.300 --> 00:12:26.850
So I'm interested here in
taking the piece, which

00:12:26.850 --> 00:12:31.140
is not suppressed.

00:12:31.140 --> 00:12:34.695
So let's just do this slowly.

00:12:38.560 --> 00:12:41.170
So there's an index A
on this guy as well.

00:12:45.350 --> 00:12:49.040
So let's write out the leading
order piece of the numerator.

00:12:49.040 --> 00:12:53.170
I've collected some i's,
put the M, the g out front.

00:13:01.172 --> 00:13:03.380
So if I take all the order
1 pieces of the numerator,

00:13:03.380 --> 00:13:04.797
then these are the
order 1 pieces.

00:13:04.797 --> 00:13:07.280
Mb is order 1.

00:13:07.280 --> 00:13:10.931
k I can replace by MbV plus q.

00:13:10.931 --> 00:13:14.015
And then there's an MbV
slash that's order 1 and an n

00:13:14.015 --> 00:13:15.500
slash over 2 n bar dot q.

00:13:15.500 --> 00:13:19.100
That's the same decomposition
we had over there.

00:13:19.100 --> 00:13:24.500
Here, because I'm interested
in certain polarization,

00:13:24.500 --> 00:13:26.270
let me pull out
that polarization.

00:13:30.930 --> 00:13:32.960
Then I have my denominator.

00:13:32.960 --> 00:13:34.733
And my denominator
we already expanded,

00:13:34.733 --> 00:13:35.900
so let's just write that in.

00:13:43.580 --> 00:13:44.960
OK, so far, so good?

00:13:47.570 --> 00:13:51.740
So this piece here is
0 because n squared

00:13:51.740 --> 00:13:54.050
is 0. n slash
squared is n squared.

00:14:04.590 --> 00:14:07.730
So then we have this piece.

00:14:07.730 --> 00:14:10.520
For this piece, 1 plus
v slash, remember,

00:14:10.520 --> 00:14:13.380
is part of a projector that
could act on the heavy quark.

00:14:13.380 --> 00:14:14.880
But there's this n
slash in the way,

00:14:14.880 --> 00:14:17.720
so we want to push it through.

00:14:17.720 --> 00:14:18.800
So we can do that.

00:14:30.832 --> 00:14:33.290
So let me write out the two
pieces from pushing it through.

00:14:35.960 --> 00:14:40.236
There's an Mb that cancels
this Mb once that term's gone.

00:14:40.236 --> 00:14:41.450
So let me do that.

00:14:44.090 --> 00:14:46.940
When I push it through, I
switch to 1 minus v slash.

00:14:50.440 --> 00:14:53.740
There's still a 1
over n dot v here.

00:14:53.740 --> 00:14:54.730
And then there's an hv.

00:14:59.830 --> 00:15:04.450
And 1 minus v slash on the
heavy quark field is 0.

00:15:04.450 --> 00:15:11.860
And then the n dot
v cancels n dot v.

00:15:11.860 --> 00:15:14.630
So if I want to
write this putting,

00:15:14.630 --> 00:15:21.100
now, this A n field inside
because the TA is inside,

00:15:21.100 --> 00:15:25.900
then I would write it like this.

00:15:30.020 --> 00:15:32.800
So the momentum here n
bar dot q is order 1.

00:15:32.800 --> 00:15:34.670
And this n bar dot
A n is order 1.

00:15:34.670 --> 00:15:38.680
So this operator is the same
size as this operator here.

00:15:52.097 --> 00:15:54.430
And that's what I was saying
that we should worry about,

00:15:54.430 --> 00:15:57.250
the fact that we can add
these gluons without any cost.

00:15:57.250 --> 00:15:59.123
And we just added
one and found out we

00:15:59.123 --> 00:16:00.790
have an operative
that's the same order.

00:16:04.610 --> 00:16:08.230
So the way you might draw this--

00:16:08.230 --> 00:16:10.480
and there's a convention
also for collinear gluons

00:16:10.480 --> 00:16:12.870
where you put a
line through them,

00:16:12.870 --> 00:16:14.590
so this is a collinear gluon--

00:16:20.400 --> 00:16:30.177
is that this guy is the
same order as this guy, OK?

00:16:30.177 --> 00:16:32.760
Well, we'll come back to this,
talk more about it in a minute.

00:16:35.650 --> 00:16:38.010
Let's consider another diagram.

00:16:38.010 --> 00:16:39.780
We attached the
gluon on the left.

00:16:39.780 --> 00:16:42.180
Let's also attach it on the
right, see what happens.

00:16:47.620 --> 00:16:54.210
So again-- QCD diagram,
doing the same thing,

00:16:54.210 --> 00:16:57.330
attaching the
gluon here, some q.

00:16:57.330 --> 00:16:59.850
This is some momentum p.

00:16:59.850 --> 00:17:03.780
And this is p minus q.

00:17:03.780 --> 00:17:07.477
This case is different
than the previous case.

00:17:07.477 --> 00:17:09.060
The reason that this
case is different

00:17:09.060 --> 00:17:12.119
is that both p and
q are collinear.

00:17:12.119 --> 00:17:16.369
And so p minus q is collinear,
too, same scaling as p and q.

00:17:27.187 --> 00:17:29.706
So this propagator
is not off-shell.

00:17:35.300 --> 00:17:37.940
In our hyperbolas, it would
live on the blue hyperbola

00:17:37.940 --> 00:17:43.490
that I drew, which is well
within the effective theory,

00:17:43.490 --> 00:17:45.658
not outside the
effective theory.

00:17:45.658 --> 00:17:47.950
So we don't want to integrate
out this propagator here.

00:17:50.950 --> 00:17:52.700
And what that means
is that there will be,

00:17:52.700 --> 00:17:56.480
in the effective theory
itself, an interaction,

00:17:56.480 --> 00:17:58.260
a Lagrangian interaction
that takes into

00:17:58.260 --> 00:17:59.135
account this diagram.

00:18:44.670 --> 00:18:47.800
So in the effective
theory, if you like,

00:18:47.800 --> 00:18:51.640
if I draw an effective
theory diagram,

00:18:51.640 --> 00:18:54.330
there will be an
effective theory diagram

00:18:54.330 --> 00:18:56.250
that allows us to
attach that gluon

00:18:56.250 --> 00:19:00.330
because this propagator
here is a propagator

00:19:00.330 --> 00:19:01.500
in the effective theory.

00:19:06.590 --> 00:19:09.422
Unlike the one that I just
erased which was off-shell

00:19:09.422 --> 00:19:11.630
and had to be integrated
out of the effective theory,

00:19:11.630 --> 00:19:17.390
this one is inside the
effective theory, OK?

00:19:17.390 --> 00:19:18.890
So adding on the
left does something

00:19:18.890 --> 00:19:20.840
different than
adding on the right.

00:19:20.840 --> 00:19:23.660
On the left, we've knocked
the quark off-shell.

00:19:23.660 --> 00:19:27.860
We add on the right,
it's close to mass shell.

00:19:27.860 --> 00:19:30.710
So we can consider
generalizing what we just

00:19:30.710 --> 00:19:34.940
did by adding more gluons.

00:19:34.940 --> 00:19:41.150
Remember that we don't
have any restrictions

00:19:41.150 --> 00:19:42.200
on how many we can add.

00:19:42.200 --> 00:19:44.030
So let's just
consider adding more.

00:19:57.630 --> 00:19:58.530
Let's add m of them.

00:20:02.769 --> 00:20:10.830
And I'll call the
momenta q1, q2, to qm.

00:20:10.830 --> 00:20:13.710
And all these propagators
here are off-shell.

00:20:19.012 --> 00:20:20.390
This is a QCD graph.

00:20:23.010 --> 00:20:25.640
When I calculate
graphs like this,

00:20:25.640 --> 00:20:29.280
if I have these gluons there,
I have to also consider

00:20:29.280 --> 00:20:30.300
cross-diagrams.

00:20:30.300 --> 00:20:35.610
So rather than trying
to draw cross-diagrams,

00:20:35.610 --> 00:20:38.040
let me just cross-gluon graphs.

00:20:45.360 --> 00:20:47.700
And what you would expect
from what we've said before

00:20:47.700 --> 00:20:49.200
is that in the
effective theory this

00:20:49.200 --> 00:20:53.490
is going to catch on to
some kind of Feynman rule

00:20:53.490 --> 00:20:57.360
that looks like
this, but then has

00:20:57.360 --> 00:21:01.740
a bunch of gluons that can
come out of the vertex,

00:21:01.740 --> 00:21:03.720
in this case m of them.

00:21:06.330 --> 00:21:08.140
That's what we expect.

00:21:08.140 --> 00:21:09.690
And so we expect
a generalization

00:21:09.690 --> 00:21:12.750
of this operator with m
fields rather than just 1.

00:21:20.020 --> 00:21:23.490
So if we do this
calculation, it actually

00:21:23.490 --> 00:21:25.200
turns out to not
be too complicated.

00:21:33.000 --> 00:21:36.780
I can include all cross-diagrams
by sum over permutations.

00:21:41.050 --> 00:21:47.760
I have one of these n bar dot A
gluons for each external gluon

00:21:47.760 --> 00:21:51.150
line with a corresponding
color factor.

00:21:51.150 --> 00:21:55.180
And I keep the largest
piece of the denominator.

00:21:55.180 --> 00:21:58.230
And I'm always just getting
the order 1 momenta.

00:22:03.520 --> 00:22:05.220
And there's a
slight complication

00:22:05.220 --> 00:22:07.540
that, when I have
a graph like this,

00:22:07.540 --> 00:22:09.450
if I look at the momentum
of this, it's q1.

00:22:09.450 --> 00:22:11.367
But if I look at the
momentum of the next one,

00:22:11.367 --> 00:22:13.155
this would be q1 plus q2.

00:22:13.155 --> 00:22:16.170
And so the denominators here are
not just simply q's, but sums

00:22:16.170 --> 00:22:16.740
of q's.

00:22:26.120 --> 00:22:26.620
OK.

00:22:26.620 --> 00:22:29.380
And these n's would
be dotted into fields.

00:22:29.380 --> 00:22:30.970
And T's would be
dotted into fields.

00:22:37.760 --> 00:22:44.110
So if we want to write this as
an effective theory operator,

00:22:44.110 --> 00:22:46.970
then we should think about
what this vertex means

00:22:46.970 --> 00:22:48.437
in the effective theory.

00:22:48.437 --> 00:22:50.020
And we should be a
little bit careful.

00:22:50.020 --> 00:22:52.690
Because what this means,
if you think about it

00:22:52.690 --> 00:22:55.090
in terms of the locality
of this diagram,

00:22:55.090 --> 00:22:57.910
is that all these gluons are
coming out of the same point.

00:22:57.910 --> 00:23:01.250
So it's like phi 4 theory where
you divide by 4 factorial.

00:23:01.250 --> 00:23:02.830
You have to be a
little bit careful

00:23:02.830 --> 00:23:05.440
because any one of these
gluons, from the point of view

00:23:05.440 --> 00:23:10.750
of the external states,
could be as equally

00:23:10.750 --> 00:23:13.190
good as an attachment.

00:23:13.190 --> 00:23:16.270
So when we put in
the gluon fields,

00:23:16.270 --> 00:23:18.453
we ought to be careful
about those factors.

00:23:18.453 --> 00:23:19.870
So this is the
right Feynman rule.

00:23:51.800 --> 00:23:56.600
And one way of just
thinking about it is we'll

00:23:56.600 --> 00:23:59.540
have m of these fields, but then
we'll divide by an m factorial.

00:24:02.750 --> 00:24:05.970
So we can write down the
complete result for the two

00:24:05.970 --> 00:24:13.068
level matching as an
operator since we just

00:24:13.068 --> 00:24:14.235
calculated all the diagrams.

00:24:37.770 --> 00:24:39.410
So we started with this current.

00:24:39.410 --> 00:24:41.250
We're in QCD.

00:24:41.250 --> 00:24:45.330
And we matched it at
tree level onto a current

00:24:45.330 --> 00:24:48.600
that I can write like this,
hiding all the complexity

00:24:48.600 --> 00:24:56.930
in this thing I call
W. I have to sum

00:24:56.930 --> 00:25:01.310
over however many attachments,
which I was previously calling

00:25:01.310 --> 00:25:02.690
m, but now I'm calling k.

00:25:28.700 --> 00:25:34.730
And if you study this guy for
a while, actually what is true

00:25:34.730 --> 00:25:36.720
is that this guy has a name.

00:25:36.720 --> 00:25:38.420
This is a momentum
space Wilson line.

00:25:52.056 --> 00:25:54.380
So what is a position
space Wilson line?

00:25:54.380 --> 00:25:56.960
That's where it really
looks more like a line.

00:26:06.850 --> 00:26:10.810
So a Wilson line is a
string of gauge fields

00:26:10.810 --> 00:26:12.550
that goes between
two points, here

00:26:12.550 --> 00:26:16.420
between minus infinity and 0.

00:26:16.420 --> 00:26:19.900
There are some
ordering to the fields

00:26:19.900 --> 00:26:21.160
because they don't commute.

00:26:21.160 --> 00:26:22.327
Because they're not abelian.

00:26:26.680 --> 00:26:28.720
And the fact that
it's a line means

00:26:28.720 --> 00:26:32.170
that we go in a straight
line between the two points.

00:26:35.370 --> 00:26:37.370
So here's a path which
is a straight line

00:26:37.370 --> 00:26:40.230
s between minus infinity and 0.

00:26:40.230 --> 00:26:44.960
And actually, this formula here,
the Fourier transform of this,

00:26:44.960 --> 00:26:48.010
is giving you the Wilson
line that I drew up--

00:26:48.010 --> 00:26:50.625
the Feynman rule that I
drew up there or the fields

00:26:50.625 --> 00:26:51.500
that I drew up there.

00:27:22.702 --> 00:27:24.850
So there's some
ordering to the fields.

00:27:24.850 --> 00:27:26.860
And what this P does
is it orders the fields

00:27:26.860 --> 00:27:27.850
in an appropriate way.

00:27:27.850 --> 00:27:30.040
Namely, it puts the guys
with the larger argument

00:27:30.040 --> 00:27:30.640
to the left.

00:27:46.510 --> 00:27:48.160
So on your homework,
you're going

00:27:48.160 --> 00:27:50.260
to do the exercise of
thinking about doing

00:27:50.260 --> 00:27:55.570
this matching for two gluons
and taking the Fourier transform

00:27:55.570 --> 00:27:57.670
this and connecting these.

00:27:57.670 --> 00:28:00.160
At least I believe
that's what I asked.

00:28:00.160 --> 00:28:02.950
That's a very good exercise
to see everything work out

00:28:02.950 --> 00:28:06.830
that I'm just describing
to you here in words.

00:28:06.830 --> 00:28:09.280
So one way of thinking about
what's happened in this

00:28:09.280 --> 00:28:11.447
effective theory-- and this
actually turns out to be

00:28:11.447 --> 00:28:12.490
generically true--

00:28:12.490 --> 00:28:16.540
is that rather than having
this embarked on a field, which

00:28:16.540 --> 00:28:19.900
was order 1, it actually can
be traded for this Wilson line

00:28:19.900 --> 00:28:21.305
object.

00:28:21.305 --> 00:28:22.930
So I just showed you
that that happened

00:28:22.930 --> 00:28:25.420
for this particular example,
but it turns out actually

00:28:25.420 --> 00:28:29.160
to be genetic, that, instead
of talking about the n

00:28:29.160 --> 00:28:31.990
bar of A field, we can
talk about this function

00:28:31.990 --> 00:28:33.670
of the field, which
is this Wilson line.

00:28:44.894 --> 00:28:46.740
Lift that for a sec.

00:28:56.660 --> 00:28:58.060
So this is true
in this operator.

00:28:58.060 --> 00:28:59.620
We just got this Wilson line.

00:28:59.620 --> 00:29:02.110
In terms of the Wilson line,
things are pretty simple.

00:29:04.780 --> 00:29:06.980
And it actually turns out
to be generically true,

00:29:06.980 --> 00:29:08.170
and we'll see that later on.

00:29:12.570 --> 00:29:14.400
And we'll also talk
about gauge invariance

00:29:14.400 --> 00:29:18.490
later on, which has
to do with this story.

00:29:18.490 --> 00:29:20.760
It turns out that this
Wilson line can also

00:29:20.760 --> 00:29:23.160
be understood from the point
of view of gauge invariance.

00:29:23.160 --> 00:29:24.840
The need for this
Wilson line can

00:29:24.840 --> 00:29:27.960
be understood from the point
of view of gauge invariance.

00:29:27.960 --> 00:29:31.120
And I can at least describe
that to you in words.

00:29:31.120 --> 00:29:35.100
So if you look at
this diagram here,

00:29:35.100 --> 00:29:38.460
we can't attach collinear
gluons to this quark.

00:29:38.460 --> 00:29:40.680
But this carries color.

00:29:40.680 --> 00:29:43.560
We can attach collinear gluons
to this quark, no problem.

00:29:43.560 --> 00:29:45.750
It doesn't knock it
off-shell or anything.

00:29:45.750 --> 00:29:49.620
So we're going to have a
problem with gauge symmetry

00:29:49.620 --> 00:29:52.080
because we have two
things that are colored.

00:29:52.080 --> 00:29:54.570
A priori, we're going to have
a problem with gauge symmetry

00:29:54.570 --> 00:29:56.190
because we have two things
of color, one of which

00:29:56.190 --> 00:29:58.380
we can't attach effective
theory fields to and one

00:29:58.380 --> 00:30:00.150
of which we can.

00:30:00.150 --> 00:30:03.000
But there's also operators
with gluons in them,

00:30:03.000 --> 00:30:04.530
which are these ones.

00:30:04.530 --> 00:30:09.380
And what effectively happens is
that the gauge transformation

00:30:09.380 --> 00:30:11.940
that used to be for
this heavy quark field,

00:30:11.940 --> 00:30:13.650
it gets moved into
this Wilson line.

00:30:13.650 --> 00:30:16.690
So this Wilson
line will transform

00:30:16.690 --> 00:30:18.690
in a way that compensates
for the transformation

00:30:18.690 --> 00:30:21.060
of this collinear quark field.

00:30:21.060 --> 00:30:24.480
And that's exactly because
the gluons here, which

00:30:24.480 --> 00:30:27.660
were kind of the corresponding
gluons in QCD for the gauge

00:30:27.660 --> 00:30:30.660
transformation, are
explicitly integrated out

00:30:30.660 --> 00:30:31.860
to give that Wilson line.

00:30:31.860 --> 00:30:34.650
So it's all tied together.

00:30:34.650 --> 00:30:37.860
We'll come back and talk about
that in more detail later.

00:30:40.440 --> 00:30:43.590
All right, so let's consider
now the effective theory now

00:30:43.590 --> 00:30:46.440
that we have some idea of how
these calculations are working.

00:30:51.340 --> 00:30:54.270
And let's consider this
SCETI effective theory.

00:30:56.980 --> 00:31:12.210
So we have a collinear mode and
an ultra soft mode with momenta

00:31:12.210 --> 00:31:14.730
that we're scaling in this way.

00:31:14.730 --> 00:31:20.820
And we also know, if we
consider the Feynman rules,

00:31:20.820 --> 00:31:24.250
we can look at what the
propagators would look like.

00:31:24.250 --> 00:31:29.040
So let's consider, first of
all, having a collinear gluon.

00:31:29.040 --> 00:31:33.360
And let's just try to think
about what kind of propagators

00:31:33.360 --> 00:31:36.180
the effective theory
is going to have.

00:31:36.180 --> 00:31:39.300
So maybe this comes
from a heavy quark.

00:31:39.300 --> 00:31:42.990
So we have this possibility
of having a collinear gluon,

00:31:42.990 --> 00:31:43.890
momentum q.

00:31:48.060 --> 00:31:51.130
We expanded the propagator
for that last time.

00:31:51.130 --> 00:31:53.970
And the important point about
this being a collinear gluon

00:31:53.970 --> 00:31:55.630
is that p and q
are the same size.

00:31:55.630 --> 00:31:58.380
So we never drop p relative
to q or q relative to p.

00:32:05.170 --> 00:32:09.070
So if we write out
the components,

00:32:09.070 --> 00:32:11.890
we did this last time.

00:32:11.890 --> 00:32:13.390
And we found that
there was really

00:32:13.390 --> 00:32:16.340
no expansion in the denominator.

00:32:16.340 --> 00:32:19.330
And in the numerator, we
could make an expansion

00:32:19.330 --> 00:32:21.940
and just keep the
leading order piece.

00:32:21.940 --> 00:32:24.935
So the propagator would
be proportional to this.

00:32:24.935 --> 00:32:27.310
There's some spin structure
as well that I'm not writing.

00:32:31.180 --> 00:32:35.800
But q of the gluon is
of order p of the quark.

00:32:35.800 --> 00:32:37.240
So nothing gets dropped.

00:32:44.663 --> 00:32:46.330
So this is going to
be a propagator that

00:32:46.330 --> 00:32:48.870
exists in the effective theory.

00:32:48.870 --> 00:32:50.230
That's what I was saying before.

00:32:59.545 --> 00:33:01.170
The other thing we
could do is we could

00:33:01.170 --> 00:33:04.080
attach an ultra soft particle.

00:33:10.498 --> 00:33:12.290
We could actually attach
it to either side,

00:33:12.290 --> 00:33:13.750
but let me focus
on the right side.

00:33:22.015 --> 00:33:23.890
So there's going to be
some ultra soft gluon.

00:33:23.890 --> 00:33:26.200
It's not collinear
to any direction.

00:33:26.200 --> 00:33:31.420
Let's call its momenta
k, call this still p.

00:33:31.420 --> 00:33:34.340
Now, k is much smaller than
p by our power counting.

00:33:38.410 --> 00:33:41.970
So the k is of order
lambda squared.

00:33:41.970 --> 00:33:45.737
So in n bar dot k is
much less than n bar dot

00:33:45.737 --> 00:33:48.394
p, which is of order lambda 0.

00:33:48.394 --> 00:33:53.590
k perp is much less than p
perp, which is of order lambda.

00:33:53.590 --> 00:33:57.100
And then the n dot
k is or order n

00:33:57.100 --> 00:34:00.920
dot p because those are
both lambda squared.

00:34:00.920 --> 00:34:02.990
So here it's not going
to be like over there.

00:34:02.990 --> 00:34:05.332
There is actually going
to be an expansion that

00:34:05.332 --> 00:34:07.165
occurs because things
are of different size.

00:34:11.639 --> 00:34:15.770
So if I only keep the leading
order terms and the propagator

00:34:15.770 --> 00:34:19.500
here, well, the numerator
I just have n bar

00:34:19.500 --> 00:34:23.068
dot p because n
bar dot k is small.

00:34:23.068 --> 00:34:24.860
And the only place that
I need to keep both

00:34:24.860 --> 00:34:26.350
is in this n dot term.

00:34:36.826 --> 00:34:38.409
So there is an
expansion that goes on.

00:34:47.210 --> 00:34:51.310
And again, if I look at how
off-shell this propagator is,

00:34:51.310 --> 00:34:54.469
it's perfectly within
the effective theory.

00:34:54.469 --> 00:35:01.360
So this is a propagator with
off-shellness that leaves it

00:35:01.360 --> 00:35:02.680
inside the effective theory.

00:35:07.160 --> 00:35:07.660
OK.

00:35:07.660 --> 00:35:09.730
So it's not far
off-shell by any means.

00:35:09.730 --> 00:35:13.330
In fact, it's just as off-shell
as the propagator over there

00:35:13.330 --> 00:35:15.530
for the collinear particles.

00:35:15.530 --> 00:35:17.260
So it doesn't really
make sense to think

00:35:17.260 --> 00:35:19.798
about treating this propagator
any different than treating

00:35:19.798 --> 00:35:22.090
this propagator from an
effective theory point of view.

00:35:26.180 --> 00:35:28.390
But you see that
the Feynman rule

00:35:28.390 --> 00:35:31.780
has to somehow know whether
you're in this situation where

00:35:31.780 --> 00:35:34.330
you need to keep the
momentum of the gluon

00:35:34.330 --> 00:35:36.580
or whether you're in this
situation where the momentum

00:35:36.580 --> 00:35:37.372
should be expanded.

00:35:40.760 --> 00:35:44.190
And we'll see how that works.

00:35:44.190 --> 00:35:46.820
So this is by way of
sort of giving you

00:35:46.820 --> 00:35:50.180
a hint as to what's to come
and what kind of complications

00:35:50.180 --> 00:35:52.010
we'll face in the
effective theory

00:35:52.010 --> 00:35:54.680
because the effective theory can
interact with collinear gluons

00:35:54.680 --> 00:35:56.210
or these ultra soft gluons.

00:35:56.210 --> 00:35:59.888
And it somehow needs to be only
keeping leading order terms.

00:35:59.888 --> 00:36:02.180
If it's really the leading
order effective theory, then

00:36:02.180 --> 00:36:03.240
we should just keep this term.

00:36:03.240 --> 00:36:05.210
We shouldn't keep these
higher order terms.

00:36:05.210 --> 00:36:07.085
But over here, we have
to keep all the terms.

00:36:11.142 --> 00:36:13.350
So what should the leading
order effective theory do?

00:36:18.190 --> 00:36:20.410
What should we demand of it?

00:36:20.410 --> 00:36:24.330
We've basically, now,
set up all the things

00:36:24.330 --> 00:36:25.830
that we need to
think about in order

00:36:25.830 --> 00:36:28.410
to figure out what the leading
order effective theory is.

00:36:31.600 --> 00:36:32.530
So let's do that.

00:36:36.370 --> 00:36:38.770
OK, so what do we demand
of this Lagrangian?

00:36:41.470 --> 00:36:45.940
It should yield the
propagator of course

00:36:45.940 --> 00:36:47.560
and, also, interactions.

00:36:53.710 --> 00:36:56.050
Within this effective
theory, it has interactions

00:36:56.050 --> 00:37:02.490
both with collinear gluons
in that diagram over there

00:37:02.490 --> 00:37:04.350
and with ultra soft gluons.

00:37:08.850 --> 00:37:11.130
And you can see
even from here why

00:37:11.130 --> 00:37:14.460
we need two different
fields because there

00:37:14.460 --> 00:37:17.430
has to be some way
of telling that we

00:37:17.430 --> 00:37:20.550
have a different propagator in
this case than in that case.

00:37:20.550 --> 00:37:23.820
Or put another way,
the external field

00:37:23.820 --> 00:37:25.290
here has a different
power counting

00:37:25.290 --> 00:37:26.590
than the external field here.

00:37:26.590 --> 00:37:28.740
So already we're kind
of seeing that we

00:37:28.740 --> 00:37:31.800
need two different gluon fields
in this effective theory,

00:37:31.800 --> 00:37:34.260
as we said earlier.

00:37:34.260 --> 00:37:39.190
So the Lagrangian has to have
interactions with both of them.

00:37:39.190 --> 00:37:41.790
It has to have both
quarks and antiquarks

00:37:41.790 --> 00:37:45.090
because remember that
collinear quarks and collinear

00:37:45.090 --> 00:37:48.870
antiquarks both existed
as leading order things.

00:37:48.870 --> 00:37:52.470
That's not like HQET where one
of them gets integrated out.

00:37:52.470 --> 00:37:54.510
And basically, that
is just the statement

00:37:54.510 --> 00:37:57.310
that, say you have a collinear
gluon going along very quickly.

00:37:57.310 --> 00:38:01.890
It can para-- create a
quark and an antiquark.

00:38:01.890 --> 00:38:03.420
And if they're,
again, collinear,

00:38:03.420 --> 00:38:06.360
that's something that has to
be allowed to happen at order

00:38:06.360 --> 00:38:08.040
1 in this effective theory.

00:38:12.510 --> 00:38:13.010
OK.

00:38:13.010 --> 00:38:13.950
So, so far, so good.

00:38:13.950 --> 00:38:17.540
This is just saying,
what kind of fields

00:38:17.540 --> 00:38:19.598
are we going to have
in this Lagrangian.

00:38:22.340 --> 00:38:26.150
This third bullet is related
to what I was just stressing,

00:38:26.150 --> 00:38:29.690
that we have to get a
leading order propagator

00:38:29.690 --> 00:38:32.672
in different situations.

00:38:32.672 --> 00:38:34.130
So somehow the
effective theory has

00:38:34.130 --> 00:38:38.930
to know something about
the size of momenta that

00:38:38.930 --> 00:38:40.610
are running through it.

00:38:45.410 --> 00:38:47.210
And if we want to be
strict about defining

00:38:47.210 --> 00:38:50.780
the effective theory and just
defining the leading order

00:38:50.780 --> 00:38:54.120
term, it's not OK
that we expand later.

00:38:54.120 --> 00:38:57.050
We really have to
expand ahead of time.

00:39:01.230 --> 00:39:05.120
And so whatever the Lagrangian
is, it should just give this.

00:39:05.120 --> 00:39:07.100
And it should just give this.

00:39:07.100 --> 00:39:10.318
And it should not
give these dots, OK?

00:39:18.980 --> 00:39:22.610
So that's what I mean by
having no additional expansion.

00:39:26.740 --> 00:39:29.660
And the final thing is
a little more subtle.

00:39:29.660 --> 00:39:34.430
And that is that we
should think ahead.

00:39:34.430 --> 00:39:36.383
So when we design
this effective theory,

00:39:36.383 --> 00:39:38.800
we're not only going to want
to describe the leading order

00:39:38.800 --> 00:39:40.330
term, but we're
also going to want

00:39:40.330 --> 00:39:41.865
to describe power corrections.

00:39:41.865 --> 00:39:43.990
Because if we can't describe
the power corrections,

00:39:43.990 --> 00:39:45.948
we don't really have an
effective field theory.

00:39:48.450 --> 00:39:50.250
So whatever we do,
we should make sure

00:39:50.250 --> 00:39:54.210
that we have a notion of what's
going on with higher order

00:39:54.210 --> 00:39:56.717
terms, that they're
well-defined things, that we

00:39:56.717 --> 00:39:58.800
can think ahead about what
the operators are going

00:39:58.800 --> 00:40:00.010
to look like.

00:40:00.010 --> 00:40:01.590
And we need that
in order to know

00:40:01.590 --> 00:40:03.750
that we can formulate those
operators and make sure

00:40:03.750 --> 00:40:06.810
they're suppressed.

00:40:06.810 --> 00:40:14.040
So another way of putting it is
that we should set things up,

00:40:14.040 --> 00:40:15.780
so we don't have
to re-set things up

00:40:15.780 --> 00:40:18.248
when we start talking
about power corrections.

00:40:33.068 --> 00:40:35.610
So we really should think about
the effective theory globally

00:40:35.610 --> 00:40:38.490
even though we're sort of
starting by formulating

00:40:38.490 --> 00:40:40.170
a leading order term.

00:40:40.170 --> 00:40:42.420
We should think about the
power corrections as well

00:40:42.420 --> 00:40:45.320
and how those interactions
are going to behave.

00:40:47.830 --> 00:40:50.152
OK, so that's saying that
we want to think about,

00:40:50.152 --> 00:40:51.610
at least, what
these dots are going

00:40:51.610 --> 00:40:53.655
to look like, what
this plus dot,

00:40:53.655 --> 00:40:56.540
dot, dot is going to look like.

00:40:56.540 --> 00:40:57.940
OK, so this is our goal.

00:40:57.940 --> 00:41:00.170
And we'll go through it slowly.

00:41:06.020 --> 00:41:08.320
So this is a top-down
effective theory.

00:41:08.320 --> 00:41:10.030
So we can start with
QCD, and then we

00:41:10.030 --> 00:41:14.420
can integrate out the
off-shell degrees of freedom.

00:41:14.420 --> 00:41:16.590
We can just formulate
from what SCET

00:41:16.590 --> 00:41:22.080
is by starting with
the QCD Lagrangian

00:41:22.080 --> 00:41:26.530
and splitting it into
the fields that we want

00:41:26.530 --> 00:41:29.660
and manipulating it.

00:41:29.660 --> 00:41:34.420
So let's start with
psi bar iD slash psi.

00:41:34.420 --> 00:41:37.135
And let's write psi in
terms of two fields.

00:41:47.850 --> 00:41:50.245
And this goes back
to our discussion

00:41:50.245 --> 00:41:51.745
when we were talking
