00:51:56.380 --> 00:51:58.480
OK, so several questions arise.

00:51:58.480 --> 00:52:00.190
What have we done?

00:52:00.190 --> 00:52:02.290
Do we like this inverse
covariant derivative?

00:52:02.290 --> 00:52:03.400
Are we happy with that?

00:52:03.400 --> 00:52:05.480
Are we unhappy with it?

00:52:05.480 --> 00:52:08.720
So what does an inverse
covariant derivative mean?

00:52:08.720 --> 00:52:11.140
Well, actually just what is
an inverse derivative mean?

00:52:11.140 --> 00:52:12.490
This is an inverse operator.

00:52:19.550 --> 00:52:21.030
So what does that mean?

00:52:24.040 --> 00:52:25.830
So the way you define
an inverse operator

00:52:25.830 --> 00:52:27.840
is exactly how you define
an inverse operator

00:52:27.840 --> 00:52:28.830
in quantum mechanics.

00:52:31.670 --> 00:52:34.775
So let me remind you of that.

00:52:34.775 --> 00:52:37.150
This is the analog of, in
quantum mechanics, having, say,

00:52:37.150 --> 00:52:38.950
a 1 over r potential.

00:52:38.950 --> 00:52:41.730
But if r is an operator, then
you have a 1 over an operator.

00:52:46.880 --> 00:52:49.330
And the way that you define
that is by the eigenvalues.

00:53:07.600 --> 00:53:14.410
So 1 over i in r dot
partial of some field

00:53:14.410 --> 00:53:19.570
i of x you can write it out
in terms of momentum space.

00:53:27.620 --> 00:53:30.310
So if we go over to momentum
space, that's the eigenbasis.

00:53:33.160 --> 00:53:34.570
And then the
eigenvalue is just 1

00:53:34.570 --> 00:53:38.795
over the momentum, this
component of the momentum.

00:53:42.840 --> 00:53:46.234
OK, so it's just the
Fourier transform of that.

