There's two different
types of momenta,

00:57:44.670 --> 00:57:47.520
as we saw in this simple
example of a gluon momenta

00:57:47.520 --> 00:57:48.720
flowing into a propagator.

00:57:48.720 --> 00:57:52.030
And we actually have
to distinguish them.

00:57:52.030 --> 00:57:54.870
And then we have to expand.

00:57:54.870 --> 00:57:56.940
So until we do these
first two steps,

00:57:56.940 --> 00:57:59.080
there's not really
anything to expand.

00:57:59.080 --> 00:58:02.127
And so once we've
distinguished those,

00:58:02.127 --> 00:58:03.960
we'll be able to say
that certain things are

00:58:03.960 --> 00:58:04.860
larger than others.

00:58:08.580 --> 00:58:10.080
And then we'll be
able to figure out

00:58:10.080 --> 00:58:11.880
what the leading or
Lagrangian actually is.

00:58:15.070 --> 00:58:17.610
OK, so let's start
with this second step.

00:58:22.300 --> 00:58:26.111
So this is step two.

00:58:26.111 --> 00:58:28.090
So remember what the
power counting was.

00:58:33.455 --> 00:58:36.280
The collinear gluons
had this scaling.

00:58:36.280 --> 00:58:43.798
The ultra soft gluons
had this scaling,

00:58:43.798 --> 00:58:45.590
which is the same as
an ultra soft momenta.

00:58:52.540 --> 00:58:54.790
And the right way of
doing this kind of thing

00:58:54.790 --> 00:58:56.710
would be to take
Feynman diagrams

00:58:56.710 --> 00:58:59.440
and do some matching
calculations,

00:58:59.440 --> 00:59:01.270
but sometimes we're
able to get away

00:59:01.270 --> 00:59:05.170
with just thinking about
doing things by writing down

00:59:05.170 --> 00:59:07.110
field relations.

00:59:07.110 --> 00:59:09.490
And that's almost true here.

00:59:09.490 --> 00:59:12.062
When we were drawing our
Feynman diagrams before,

00:59:12.062 --> 00:59:14.270
if you think about one gluon,
this is certainly true.

00:59:14.270 --> 00:59:17.380
So we drew Feynman
diagrams before.

00:59:17.380 --> 00:59:25.960
We had this one, and we had
this one, ultra soft collinear.

00:59:25.960 --> 00:59:28.760
And we just consider
one at a time.

00:59:28.760 --> 00:59:31.030
So we could just
think of adding them.

00:59:31.030 --> 00:59:34.010
And that's kind of almost true.

00:59:34.010 --> 00:59:37.060
It turns out that it's
true up to some terms

00:59:37.060 --> 00:59:41.055
that we don't care about
for the moment, OK?

00:59:56.480 --> 00:59:58.639
But these terms are
power suppressed.

01:00:04.870 --> 01:00:07.870
And we'll see where
they come from later on.

01:00:07.870 --> 01:00:09.370
So the way you can
think about this,

01:00:09.370 --> 01:00:12.100
if you ignore that
complication, is

01:00:12.100 --> 01:00:16.060
that you really just divide the
gauge field into two pieces.

01:00:16.060 --> 01:00:18.370
There's one place that you've
perhaps seen that before,

01:00:18.370 --> 01:00:20.657
when you talk about a
background gauge field, right?

01:00:20.657 --> 01:00:22.990
You say you have a quantum
field and a background field.

01:00:22.990 --> 01:00:25.750
And that's very nice if you
go to background field gauge.

01:00:25.750 --> 01:00:27.370
And that's kind of
physically what's

01:00:27.370 --> 01:00:29.800
going on here because we
have two different modes that

01:00:29.800 --> 01:00:31.660
have different wavelengths.

01:00:31.660 --> 01:00:33.250
These guys are really
long wavelength.

01:00:33.250 --> 01:00:34.570
These guys are
shorter wavelength.

01:00:34.570 --> 01:00:36.330
Remember that the p
squared of these guys

01:00:36.330 --> 01:00:39.310
is much larger than the
p squared of these guys.

01:00:42.550 --> 01:00:45.760
And think about this
formula in that way,

01:00:45.760 --> 01:00:55.530
that this is like a
classical background

01:00:55.530 --> 01:01:10.620
field to the Cn and the A n mu
since the p ultra soft squared

01:01:10.620 --> 01:01:15.810
had a scaling which was lambda
to the fourth lambda squared

01:01:15.810 --> 01:01:16.920
squared.

01:01:16.920 --> 01:01:20.430
And that's much smaller than
p collinear squared, which

01:01:20.430 --> 01:01:23.920
was q squared lambda squared.

01:01:23.920 --> 01:01:27.180
So that's saying that this guy
has much larger wavelength,

01:01:27.180 --> 01:01:30.800
a long wavelength mode to
these short distance modes.

01:01:30.800 --> 01:01:33.300
So we can think of this
as a slowly varying

01:01:33.300 --> 01:01:34.410
classical background.

01:01:34.410 --> 01:01:36.493
And that's one way of
thinking about this formula.

01:01:36.493 --> 01:01:39.120
We'll exploit that a little
bit later on as well.

01:01:45.270 --> 01:01:47.840
So now that we have
the sum of them,

01:01:47.840 --> 01:01:50.600
we can just think about how big
one is relative to the other.

01:01:50.600 --> 01:01:52.220
And actually, the coefficient
that's between them

01:01:52.220 --> 01:01:53.887
doesn't really matter
too much for that.

01:02:03.510 --> 01:02:05.870
So let's think about
the power counting

01:02:05.870 --> 01:02:07.440
I already wrote on the board.

01:02:10.380 --> 01:02:11.895
So the power counting
is that n bar

01:02:11.895 --> 01:02:14.610
dot A n is order lambda
to the 0 and so is

01:02:14.610 --> 01:02:19.560
much greater than the
n bar dot A ultra soft,

01:02:19.560 --> 01:02:21.780
which is order lambda squared.

01:02:21.780 --> 01:02:25.400
Same for A perp n,
that's of order lambda.

01:02:25.400 --> 01:02:28.395
That's much greater
than A perp ultra soft.

01:02:31.770 --> 01:02:34.590
And so those two formulas
mean that it would never

01:02:34.590 --> 01:02:36.510
have a comparison
between this and this.

01:02:36.510 --> 01:02:38.070
I can always drop
the smaller one.

01:02:40.820 --> 01:02:43.640
And just like our
momentum, there's

01:02:43.640 --> 01:02:45.470
one case where
that's not true where

01:02:45.470 --> 01:02:47.820
we have to keep both of them.

01:02:47.820 --> 01:02:50.499
And that's for the
n dot A component.

01:02:57.490 --> 01:02:59.170
So here's something
we can drop, n bar

01:02:59.170 --> 01:03:04.951
dot A ultra soft and
A perp ultra soft.

01:03:04.951 --> 01:03:10.720
That leading order
can be dropped, OK?

01:03:10.720 --> 01:03:12.730
So that's what we're
going to do and step two.

01:03:23.260 --> 01:03:25.360
Step three corresponds
to dropping momentum

01:03:25.360 --> 01:03:26.830
relative to another momentum.

01:03:32.990 --> 01:03:35.150
So there was an expansion
of the propagator

01:03:35.150 --> 01:03:37.480
in the case where we had
an ultra soft and collinear

01:03:37.480 --> 01:03:38.290
at the same time.

01:03:55.918 --> 01:03:57.460
And let's just write
that down again,

01:03:57.460 --> 01:03:58.918
but let's keep the
next order term.

01:04:06.970 --> 01:04:10.390
And I'll ignore the
numerator since just looking

01:04:10.390 --> 01:04:13.600
at the denominator will
give us enough information

01:04:13.600 --> 01:04:14.835
for this discussion.

01:04:18.720 --> 01:04:20.440
We could do the numerator, too.

01:04:20.440 --> 01:04:22.335
It would just lead
to more terms.

01:04:28.870 --> 01:04:31.410
So there are some terms
that I can expand.

01:04:31.410 --> 01:04:34.230
And then I get the
propagator squared,

01:04:34.230 --> 01:04:38.700
or I get a P squared squared,
because I expanded something

01:04:38.700 --> 01:04:40.827
in the denominator back
into the numerator.

01:04:44.410 --> 01:04:48.150
So the next order term
comes from a dot product

01:04:48.150 --> 01:04:52.540
in the perp momenta because
the Pn perp is large.

01:04:52.540 --> 01:04:56.178
And so we get a term with
two k ultra soft dot Pn perp

01:04:56.178 --> 01:04:57.720
that corrects the
leading order term.

01:04:57.720 --> 01:05:02.470
And that's the first
sub-leading term.

01:05:02.470 --> 01:05:04.680
So if you think about the
power counting of these,

01:05:04.680 --> 01:05:07.440
this guy is lambda
to the minus 2.

01:05:07.440 --> 01:05:09.270
And this guy is
lambda to the minus 1.

01:05:15.770 --> 01:05:18.440
OK, so there has to be something
in the effective theory that,

01:05:18.440 --> 01:05:20.780
at higher order, will
reproduce this second guy.

01:05:29.810 --> 01:05:43.370
There will be some power
suppressed Feynman rule in SCET

01:05:43.370 --> 01:05:45.230
to reproduce this second term.

01:05:59.530 --> 01:06:01.740
So what that means is
that you can't just

01:06:01.740 --> 01:06:06.420
think that you ignore
this guy completely,

01:06:06.420 --> 01:06:08.850
this k ultra soft perp.

01:06:08.850 --> 01:06:12.390
You might just say, well, I just
set all the k ultra soft perps

01:06:12.390 --> 01:06:16.710
and the k ultra
soft minuses to 0.

01:06:16.710 --> 01:06:18.210
And that would be
something that you

01:06:18.210 --> 01:06:22.380
can get away with, if your
careful, at lowest order.

01:06:22.380 --> 01:06:24.445
But at sub-leading
order, you can't.

01:06:24.445 --> 01:06:27.540
You need to think
that they exist, too.

01:06:27.540 --> 01:06:31.900
So whatever formalism we develop
should not set them to 0.

01:06:31.900 --> 01:06:35.380
And that was one of my
bullets that you should

01:06:35.380 --> 01:06:37.158
think a little bit ahead.

01:06:37.158 --> 01:06:38.950
And this is me thinking
ahead, that I'm not

01:06:38.950 --> 01:06:41.410
going to be able to just set
those momentum exactly to 0.

01:06:41.410 --> 01:06:43.202
I'm going to need them
when I start talking

01:06:43.202 --> 01:06:44.695
about sub-leading terms.

01:06:49.890 --> 01:07:00.600
OK, so we expand just
like we don't throw away

01:07:00.600 --> 01:07:02.850
the sub-leading gauge
fields because we need those

01:07:02.850 --> 01:07:04.428
at sub-leading order as well.

01:07:04.428 --> 01:07:05.970
We neglect them in
the leading order,

01:07:05.970 --> 01:07:09.182
but we have to sort of
think that they exist still.

01:07:09.182 --> 01:07:10.890
And with momenta, it's
a little different

01:07:10.890 --> 01:07:13.230
since fields carry momenta.

01:07:13.230 --> 01:07:16.290
And so what you should think
is that the fields are allowed

01:07:16.290 --> 01:07:18.540
to sort of carry these
momenta, but the Feynman rules

01:07:18.540 --> 01:07:21.228
of the leading order theory
are just not sensitive to them.

01:07:21.228 --> 01:07:22.770
And that's the right
way of thinking.

01:07:58.030 --> 01:08:00.700
OK, so what we need
is an expansion

01:08:00.700 --> 01:08:02.940
of the theory that will do this.

01:08:02.940 --> 01:08:04.690
And that's called the
multipole expansion.

01:08:26.142 --> 01:08:27.600
So let me remind
you of some things

01:08:27.600 --> 01:08:30.750
about multipole expansion.

01:08:30.750 --> 01:08:33.180
Well, a multipole expansion
you see in electromagnetism,

01:08:33.180 --> 01:08:34.590
remember?

01:08:34.590 --> 01:08:37.410
You look at a charge
distribution far away.

01:08:37.410 --> 01:08:39.951
You see the total interval
over that charge distribution

01:08:39.951 --> 01:08:40.784
and then the dipole.

01:08:43.817 --> 01:08:45.359
That's the usual
thing that you think

01:08:45.359 --> 01:08:47.484
of when you think of the
words multipole expansion.

01:08:47.484 --> 01:08:58.510
You think of E&M. And
it's similar here,

01:08:58.510 --> 01:09:01.600
except we're doing
it for fields.

01:09:01.600 --> 01:09:08.010
So in position space, it's
similar to this where we expand

01:09:08.010 --> 01:09:10.380
and we neglect some coordinates.

01:09:10.380 --> 01:09:13.109
So let me show you how a
multipole expansion works

01:09:13.109 --> 01:09:14.744
in one dimension
in position space.

01:09:18.920 --> 01:09:20.630
So let's consider the following.

01:09:20.630 --> 01:09:26.164
Consider an integral
dx psi bar of x A

01:09:26.164 --> 01:09:30.890
of 0 psi bar of psi of x.

01:09:30.890 --> 01:09:33.500
So one of the fields I
stuck at 0 I expanded out

01:09:33.500 --> 01:09:37.609
the coordinate around 0, whereas
the other ones I kept the x.

01:09:37.609 --> 01:09:42.649
Let's see what this does
for the momentum space

01:09:42.649 --> 01:09:43.910
by Fourier transforming it--

01:09:46.720 --> 01:10:04.187
so some momenta,
some phases, and then

01:10:04.187 --> 01:10:05.395
some momentum space vehicles.

01:10:12.590 --> 01:10:14.360
And I just put 0
because I put one

01:10:14.360 --> 01:10:16.730
of the fields in the
coordinate space at 0.

01:10:20.000 --> 01:10:20.750
Do the x integral.

01:10:26.270 --> 01:10:29.810
So I got a delta function
that says P1 is equal to P2

01:10:29.810 --> 01:10:31.580
because I didn't have
anything in the k.

01:10:39.860 --> 01:10:42.440
And this is kind of along
the lines of what we want.

01:10:42.440 --> 01:10:46.490
It says that the momentum P1
is equal to the momentum P2.

01:10:46.490 --> 01:10:50.270
And that's like expanding in k.

01:10:50.270 --> 01:10:55.020
So if we think about having
some Feynman diagram where

01:10:55.020 --> 01:11:04.050
we have P1 and P2
and some k coming in,

01:11:04.050 --> 01:11:07.100
if we want in some component
that P1 is equal to P2,

01:11:07.100 --> 01:11:08.300
then this is achieving that.

01:11:19.450 --> 01:11:22.620
OK, so this is the
analog of the kind

01:11:22.620 --> 01:11:25.770
of expanding coordinates
that you do in E&M. Expanding

01:11:25.770 --> 01:11:28.060
into coordinates of a field
is doing the same thing.

01:11:28.060 --> 01:11:30.300
It's giving a
momentum conservation

01:11:30.300 --> 01:11:32.370
that ignores the momentum
conjugate to that

01:11:32.370 --> 01:11:33.660
coordinate that I expand in.

01:11:42.367 --> 01:11:44.200
So what would the next
order term look like?

01:11:59.100 --> 01:12:03.100
So we're still here
in one dimension.

01:12:03.100 --> 01:12:04.900
If you think about
the expansion,

01:12:04.900 --> 01:12:09.070
the next order term would
be a term like this,

01:12:09.070 --> 01:12:12.570
then at x equals 0.

01:12:12.570 --> 01:12:13.070
Sorry.

01:12:15.820 --> 01:12:20.697
I don't really need dot
since this is one dimension.

01:12:23.318 --> 01:12:25.360
So that would be the next
term in a Taylor series

01:12:25.360 --> 01:12:28.720
of the field about x equals 0.

01:12:28.720 --> 01:12:35.680
And if you do the same thing,
Fourier transform this guy,

01:12:35.680 --> 01:12:37.570
you can work out that
you get the following.

01:12:53.220 --> 01:12:55.910
OK, so the derivative
here on the coordinate,

01:12:55.910 --> 01:12:59.135
that comes with k, momentum.

01:12:59.135 --> 01:13:01.010
Because I should Fourier
transform the field,

01:13:01.010 --> 01:13:04.430
then take the derivative,
then set the coordinate to 0,

01:13:04.430 --> 01:13:06.890
so I can still get a k.

01:13:06.890 --> 01:13:10.600
And this x actually just ends
up leading to a delta prime.

01:13:10.600 --> 01:13:12.080
You can write it
as a derivative.

01:13:12.080 --> 01:13:14.850
And x can be written as a
derivative in momentum space.

01:13:14.850 --> 01:13:17.630
And then it's a derivative
on the delta function.

01:13:17.630 --> 01:13:22.980
OK, so that's what the second
order term would look like.

01:13:22.980 --> 01:13:25.400
So if you were to
think like this,

01:13:25.400 --> 01:13:27.500
you have some kind
of Feynman rule

01:13:27.500 --> 01:13:30.230
that's proportional
to a delta prime.

01:13:30.230 --> 01:13:33.710
And then however you
deal with a delta prime,

01:13:33.710 --> 01:13:36.197
if you're Feynman rule had a
delta prime, what you would do

01:13:36.197 --> 01:13:37.530
is you would integrate by parts.

01:13:37.530 --> 01:13:38.990
And then the delta
prime would start taking

01:13:38.990 --> 01:13:40.190
derivatives of other things.

01:13:44.910 --> 01:13:47.098
So that is a possible
route, but we're not

01:13:47.098 --> 01:13:48.140
going to take that route.

01:13:48.140 --> 01:13:49.640
We're going to do
something simpler.

01:13:53.080 --> 01:13:58.180
So we could formulate the
multipole expansion in position

01:13:58.180 --> 01:14:01.180
space like that,
but we're actually

01:14:01.180 --> 01:14:03.400
going to formulate
it in momentum space.

01:14:20.590 --> 01:14:22.090
So we're going to
do the same thing,

01:14:22.090 --> 01:14:23.882
but we're going to do
it in momentum space.

01:14:26.310 --> 01:14:28.950
What are some
reasons to do that?

01:14:28.950 --> 01:14:30.660
Well, when you do
Feynman diagrams,

01:14:30.660 --> 01:14:32.970
you do them in momentum space.

01:14:32.970 --> 01:14:35.650
So if we've already formulated
things in momentum space,

01:14:35.650 --> 01:14:37.930
then we'll immediately
get the Feynman rules

01:14:37.930 --> 01:14:40.230
we want to do loop integrals
and stuff like that.

01:14:44.088 --> 01:14:46.630
So that's an advantage of the
momentum space is that you more

01:14:46.630 --> 01:14:48.310
directly get the
Feynman rules you want

01:14:48.310 --> 01:14:49.930
and the diagrams in
the form you want.

01:14:54.590 --> 01:14:58.340
It simplifies, actually,
slightly the formulation

01:14:58.340 --> 01:15:08.000
or somewhat the formulation
of gauge transformations,

01:15:08.000 --> 01:15:09.440
which we'll talk about later on.

01:15:12.210 --> 01:15:17.130
And what I think is a
nice kind of advantage

01:15:17.130 --> 01:15:21.360
is where the momentum expansion
sits is in the propagator,

01:15:21.360 --> 01:15:22.200
not in the vertices.

01:15:30.320 --> 01:15:32.210
We don't get Feynman
rules with delta primes,

01:15:32.210 --> 01:15:36.080
but we then have to integrate
by parts to understand.

01:15:36.080 --> 01:15:38.330
We just immediately
get insertions

01:15:38.330 --> 01:15:40.700
on propagators which would
correspond to the derivatives

01:15:40.700 --> 01:15:42.560
that I would take
from integrating

01:15:42.560 --> 01:15:45.320
that delta prime by parts.

01:15:51.780 --> 01:15:57.080
So this term that we saw before
that looked like a propagator

01:15:57.080 --> 01:15:58.410
squared--

01:15:58.410 --> 01:16:01.775
which was when we were
sitting in momentum space

01:16:01.775 --> 01:16:03.770
and we expanded the
propagator to second order.

01:16:07.170 --> 01:16:13.040
So we had this term that was
ultra soft perp dot Pn perp.

01:16:13.040 --> 01:16:16.120
And then it had this
denominator that was squared.

01:16:16.120 --> 01:16:17.850
If you ask where in
the effective theory

01:16:17.850 --> 01:16:21.540
is that, what is going to be the
thing that corresponds to that,

01:16:21.540 --> 01:16:27.330
it's going to correspond to
some collinear propagator

01:16:27.330 --> 01:16:29.550
with an insertion on it.

01:16:29.550 --> 01:16:31.200
And the insertion
gives this numerator.

01:16:31.200 --> 01:16:33.710
And then I have two propagators.

01:16:33.710 --> 01:16:35.220
And that gives the
two denominators.

01:16:39.910 --> 01:16:42.690
OK, so that's how that term
is going to come about.

01:16:52.497 --> 01:16:54.330
So there will be some
sub-leading Lagrangian

01:16:54.330 --> 01:16:57.480
that I could call L1 that I
can insert on the propagator.

01:16:57.480 --> 01:17:01.750
And that would give rise to
these terms that we were saying

01:17:01.750 --> 01:17:04.240
were higher order.

01:17:04.240 --> 01:17:08.550
OK, so we have to figure
out how to do this.

01:17:08.550 --> 01:17:11.050
And I will just give a little
bit of a picture for it today,

01:17:11.050 --> 01:17:12.800
and then we'll continue
with it next time.

01:17:15.460 --> 01:17:17.905
So I'm going to have
to back up a bit.

01:17:17.905 --> 01:17:20.155
So let's back up to the
Lagrangian that we had before.

01:17:24.220 --> 01:17:27.520
And I want to just
introduce, since we were not

01:17:27.520 --> 01:17:29.890
close to being done--

01:17:29.890 --> 01:17:33.520
we had sort of started down the
path, but we weren't done yet.

01:17:33.520 --> 01:17:37.180
Let me give a slightly
